    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Ockham. Wednesdy Evg. 2nd Decr. 1835.</p>
      <p>My Dearest. The Hen is here, &amp; on Saturday we both return to Fordhook, so remember that after Saturday I shall be there. I am longing to hear from you, my dear, &amp; it seems very odd to be so long without.-- I have this morning looked through all the &amp;c which came by the Cab. I did not</p>
      <p>know you meant to buy that beautiful work on Ornithology.</p>
      <p>This reminds me of the Bird. Mama desires me to say that she will send you a true &amp; particular account of it, tomorrow.--</p>
      <p>Miss D'Espourria thinks me improving very much. She is pleased with the Bird.</p>
      <p>Charlotte rode here today, to explain that as Hester is not yet returned &amp; Locke is very unwell, she could not leave home. I think there is some reason in this. Locke has had a very bad cold, &amp; Charlotte seems dissatisfied</p>
      <p>with his present state. She is very sorry not to come, &amp; Miss D'Espourria laments much on account of the Duetts.</p>
      <p>Charlotte only got my Sunday's letter yesterday, which is very odd.-- I find Emily has been entitled in some of the newspapers, "the Modern Diana." I am sorry for it.--</p>
      <p>I forgot to tell you yesterday that Mrs Speier was confined the very morning I called, &amp; of course I did not go in. She has a girl, &amp; is going on well.--</p>
      <p>The carriage, the chariot I mean,</p>
      <p>is gone to Guildford to be repaired. This kicking wretch is a nuisance, for now there are only two available. I find the Hen thinks it important for me to drive out regularly, at least nearly every day.--</p>
      <p>My key is lost. Diligent search has been made, with no success. It is chiefly George's fault. I believe the only thing to be done, is to send the box to , who will put an entire new lock. I have none of my dressing things to use, which is rather inconvenient.-- The Hen</p>
      <p>is puzzling herself as to where the picture of me can be put here, &amp; is yet satisfied with nothing. Did you call on Mrs Carpenter in Town?--</p>
      <p>I read the prayers this morning, &amp; do not think it hurts me.--</p>
      <p>My dearest, I felt very dismal last night. It was stormy, &amp; I had no mate to scold or to pet me.-- Hewett sleeps in my dressing room.--</p>
      <p>I believe I must end, for it is past 8 o'clock.--</p>
      <p>Your most affecte Birdie A. A. K.</p>
    </div></body>
